gside patterns of reciprocity and economies of mutual obligation, especially within the context of patronage relationships (whether secular, spiritual, literal or symbolic). Through closeanalysis of a wide selection of sources in the vernacular and Latin (including the Guthlac poems of the Exeter Book, Old English verse epitaphs, the acrostic poetry of Abbo of Fleury, the Encomium Emmae Reginae and Libellus Æthelwoldi Episcopi), the study examines how texts sustain dual ways of seeing and understanding power, generating a range of imaginative possibilities along with tensions, ambiguities and instances of disguise or euphemism. It also advances new arguments about the ideology and rhetoric of power in the early medieval period. Catherine A.M. Clarke is Professor in English, University of Southampton.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian antiquitieszEngland. 0aCivilization, Anglo-Saxon. 0aEnglish poetryyOld English, ca. 450-1100xHistory and criticism. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zEngland. 0aMonasterieszEngland. 0aPower (Social sciences) in literature. 0aPower (Social sciences)zEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPower (Social sciences)zGreat BritainxHistory. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Saxon England.  aEarly Medieval.  aEconomies.  aHierarchies.  aMedieval.  aPatronage.  aPower.  aReciprocity.  aTexts.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615872840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846158728423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846158728/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles